<h3><span id=3D"The_integral_of_the_convolution">The integral of the convol=
ution</span></h3>

<p>When all treatments are finished, what was the <em>total</em> medicine u=
sage? This is the <strong>integral of the convolution</strong>. (A few minu=
tes ago, that phrase would have you jumping out of a window.)</p>

<p>But it's a simple calculation. Our plan gives each patient <code>sum([3 =
2 1]) =3D 6</code> units of medicine. And we have <code>sum([1 2 3 4 5]) =
=3D 15</code> patients. The total usage is just <code>6 x 15 =3D 90</code> =
units.</p>

<p>Wow, that was easy: the usage for the <em>entire</em> convolution is jus=
t the product of the subtotals!</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/56e822f91d16dfbb8f13a0a8d52d0b46.png" width=3D"168" height=3D"41=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\int (f * g) =3D \int f \cdot \int g }" class=3D"tex=
"></p>

<p>I hope this clicks intuitively. Note that this trick works for convoluti=
on, but not integrals in general. For example:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/78f2d953a7a319e8866bcc10aa892a79.png" width=3D"165" height=3D"41=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{ \int (x \cdot x) \ne \int x \cdot \int x }" class=
=3D"tex"></p>

