<h3><span id=3D"And_in_reverse">And in reverse...</span></h3>

<p>The convolution theorem works this way too:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/c5a0816925f9e3aa674885d90abe00b2.png" width=3D"99" height=3D"25"=
 alt=3D"\displaystyle{fg \xrightarrow{\mathscr{F}} F * G}" class=3D"tex"></=
p>

<p><strong>Regular multiplication in the regular world is fancy multiplicat=
ion in the fancy world.</strong></p>

<p>Cool, eh? Instead of multiplying two functions like some cave dweller, p=
ut on your monocle, convolve the Fourier Transforms, and and convert to the=
 time domain:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/6869aaa36d056ce64f590d5d92220d83.png" width=3D"144" height=3D"21=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{fg =3D \mathscr{F}^{-1} \lbrace F*G \rbrace}" class=
=3D"tex"></p>

<p>I'm not saying this is fun, just that it's possible. If your French frie=
nd has a gnarly calculation they're struggling with, it might look like ari=
thmetic to you.</p>

<h3><span id=3D"Mini_proof">Mini proof</span></h3>

<p>Remember how we said the integral of a convolution was a multiplication =
