<h2><span id=3D"Part_5_Applications">Part 5: Applications</span></h2>

<p>The trick with convolution is finding a useful "program" (kernel) to app=
ly to your input. Here's a few examples.</p>

<h3><span id=3D"Moving_averages">Moving averages</span></h3>

<p>Let's say you want a moving average between neighboring items in a list.=
 That is half of each element, added together:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/4e9c801fbbc424a674e4e466d939a091.png" width=3D"113" height=3D"38=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\frac{a + b}{2} =3D \frac{a}{2} + \frac{b}{2}}" clas=
s=3D"tex"></p>

<p>This is a "multiplication program" of <code>[0.5 0.5]</code> convolved w=
ith our list:</p>

<pre><code>ListConvolve[{1, 4, 9, 16, 25}, {0.5, 0.5}, {1, -1}, 0]=20
{0.5, 2.5, 6.5, 12.5, 20.5, 12.5}
</code></pre>

<p>We can perform a moving average with a single operation. Neat!</p>

<p>A 3-element moving average would be <code>[.33 .33 .33]</code>, a weight=
ed average could be <code>[.5 .25 .25]</code>.</p>

<h3><span id=3D"Derivatives">Derivatives</span></h3>

<p>The derivative finds the difference between neighboring values. Here's t=
he plan: <code>[1 -1]</code></p>

<pre><code>ListConvolve[{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, {1, -1}, {1, -1}, 0]=20
{1, 1, 1, 1, 1, -5}                         // -5 since we ran out of entri=
es

ListConvolve[{1, 4, 9, 16, 25}, {1, -1}, {1, -1}, 0]=20
{1, 3, 5, 7, 9, -25}                        // discrete derivative is 2x + =
1
</code></pre>

<p>With a simple kernel, we can find a useful math property on a discrete l=
ist. And to get a second derivative, just apply the derivative convolution =
twice:</p>

<p><code>F * [1 -1] * [1 -1]</code></p>

<p>As a shortcut, we can precompute the final convolutions (<code>[1 -1] * =
[1 -1]</code> ) and get:</p>

<pre><code>ListConvolve[{1, -1}, {1,-1}, {1, -1}, 0]=20
{1, -2, 1}
</code></pre>

<p>Now we have a <em>single</em> kernel <code>[1, -2, 1]</code> that gets t=
he second derivative of a list:</p>

<pre><code>ListConvolve[{1, 4, 9, 16, 25}, {1, -2, 1}, {1, -1}, 0]=20
{1, 2, 2, 2, 2, -34, 25}
</code></pre>

<p>Excluding the boundary items, we get the expected second derivative:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/93d03b535aa28ab5c13b0e3d7ef4dec2.png" width=3D"147" height=3D"23=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{x^2 \xrightarrow{d/dx} 2x \xrightarrow{d/dx} 2}" cla=
ss=3D"tex"></p>

<h3><span id=3D"Blurring_unblurring_images">Blurring / unblurring images</s=
pan></h3>

<p>An image blur is essentially a convolution of your image with some "blur=
ring kernel":</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/a133d2923fb791fe5e9bd5474083ada4.png" width=3D"178" height=3D"17=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\text{blurred} =3D \text{image} * \text{blur}}" clas=
s=3D"tex"></p>

<p>The blur of our 2D image requires a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Kernel_(image_processing)">2D average</a>:</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/convolution/convolution-blur-wikipedia.png.webp"=
 type=3D"image/webp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained=
.com/wp-content/uploads/convolution/convolution-blur-wikipedia.png" alt=3D"=
Kernel__image_processing__-_Wikipedia" class=3D"webpexpress-processed"></pi=
cture></p>

<p>Can we undo the blur? Yep! With our friend the Convolution Theorem, we c=
an do:</p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/a133d2923fb791fe5e9bd5474083ada4.png" width=3D"178" height=3D"17=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\text{blurred} =3D \text{image} * \text{blur}}" clas=
s=3D"tex"></p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/1e2717feb61734bf83d7818c909d24a5.png" width=3D"250" height=3D"19=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{blurred} \rbrace =3D \math=
scr{F} \lbrace \text{image} * \text{blur} \rbrace}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/45f6a8360051ab4ec3ba8e5af159b539.png" width=3D"270" height=3D"19=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{blurred} \rbrace =3D \math=
scr{F} \lbrace \text{image} \rbrace \mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{blur} \rbrace=
}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/417952a1063203f96d0b0428209b56fd.png" width=3D"203" height=3D"44=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\frac{ \mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{blurred} \rbrace }{=
\mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{blur} \rbrace} =3D \mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{imag=
e} \rbrace }" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p><img src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-latexrende=
r/pictures/ac0a303f5414c3148279e482d396cae1.png" width=3D"224" height=3D"44=
" alt=3D"\displaystyle{\mathscr{F}^{-1} \lbrace \frac{ \mathscr{F} \lbrace =
\text{blurred} \rbrace }{\mathscr{F} \lbrace \text{blur} \rbrace} \rbrace =
=3D \text{image}}" class=3D"tex"></p>

<p>Whoa! We can recover the original image by dividing out the blur. Convol=
ution is a simple multiplication in the frequency domain, and <em>deconvolu=
tion</em> is a simple division in the frequency domain.</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/convolution/image-blur.png.webp" type=3D"image/w=
ebp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/=
uploads/convolution/image-blur.png" alt=3D"image-blur" class=3D"webpexpress=
-processed"></picture></p>

<p>A short while back, the concept of "deblurring by dividing Fourier Trans=
forms" was gibberish to me. While it can be daunting mathematically, it's g=
etting simpler conceptually.</p>

