<ul>
<li>Wikipedia on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deconvolution">de=
convolution</a>,  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deblurring">debl=
urring</a>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"http://www.robots.ox.ac.uk/~az/lectures/ia/lect3.pdf">Image =
Restoration Lecture</a>, <a href=3D"http://user.engineering.uiowa.edu/~dip/=
LECTURE/PreProcessing4.html#invconvolution">another one</a>, and <a href=3D=
"http://fourier.eng.hmc.edu/e161/demos/e161_demo4.html">example for above</=
a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://www.mathworks.com/help/images/deblurring-images-usin=
g-the-blind-deconvolution-algorithm.html">Blind deconvolution</a> is when y=
ou don't know the blur kernel (make a guess)</li>
</ul>

<h3><span id=3D"Algorithm_Trick_Multiplication">Algorithm Trick: Multiplica=
tion</span></h3>

<p>What is a number? A list of digits:</p>

<pre><code>1234 =3D 1000 + 200 + 30 + 4 =3D [1000 200 30 4]
5678 =3D 5000 + 600 + 70 + 8 =3D [5000 600 70 8]
</code></pre>

<p>And what is regular, grade-school multiplication? A digit-by-digit convo=
lution! We sweep one list of digits by the other, multiplying and adding as=
 we go:</p>

<p><picture><source srcset=3D"https://betterexplained.com/wp-content/webp-e=
xpress/webp-images/uploads/convolution/gradeschoolalgorithm.png.webp" type=
=3D"image/webp"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://betterexplained.com/=
wp-content/uploads/convolution/gradeschoolalgorithm.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"=
webpexpress-processed"></picture></p>

<p><a href=3D"https://pythonandr.com/2015/10/13/karatsuba-multiplication-al=
gorithm-python-code/">Source</a></p>

<p>We can perform the calculation by convolving the lists of digits (<a hre=
f=3D"https://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=3DListConvolve%5B%7B1000%2C+200%=
2C+30%2C+4%7D%2C+%7B8%2C+70%2C+600%2C+5000%7D%2C+%7B1%2C+-1%7D%2C+0%5D">wol=
fram alpha</a>):</p>

<pre><code>ListConvolve[{1000, 200, 30, 4}, {8, 70, 600, 5000}, {1, -1}, 0]
{8000, 71600, 614240, 5122132, 1018280, 152400, 20000}

sum {8000, 71600, 614240, 5122132, 1018280, 152400, 20000}
7006652
</code></pre>

<p>Note that we pre-flip one of the lists (it gets swapped in the convoluti=
on later), and the intermediate calculations are a bit different. But, comb=
ining the subtotals gives the expected result.</p>

<h3><span id=3D"Faster_Convolutions">Faster Convolutions</span></h3>

