For some insight into why convolution in the TD is multiplication in the FD=
, have a look at this article: <a href=3D"https://disq.us/url?url=3Dhttps%3=
A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fderiving-convolution-from-first-principles-=
4ff124888028%3Av6lrtk87qUaIy880mz5ZL6Bw3X0&amp;cuid=3D4696425" rel=3D"nofol=
low noopener" target=3D"_blank" title=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/der=
iving-convolution-from-first-principles-4ff124888028">https://towardsdatasc=
ience....</a></p><p>(Actually it has a reference with a more detailed expla=
nation which I found better).</p><p>The short version is that convolution i=
s equivalent to matrix multiplication by a circulant matrix. Well circulant=
 matrices have the very interesting property of ALL sharing the same eigenv=
ectors, which precisely are the complex exponentials forming the DFT basis.=
</p></div></div><span class=3D"post-media"><ul data-role=3D"post-media-list=
