>Almost.  Multiplication is fancy <b>correlation</b>.  Take the digits of a=
 N digit number X and a M digit number Y, treat these as len(N) and len(M) =
vectors, and perform a correlation.   By correlation I mean a signal proces=
sing correlation, not a statistical analysis 101 correlation.  The latter i=
s the multiplication followed by weighted summation at zero lag, while the =
former is unweighted and includes all the possible non-trivial lags.</p><p>=
This yields a N+M+1 element vector.  Save the mod 10 components in the elem=
ents (giving you digits of the multiplication w/o any carries), and add the=
 quotient to the next element (if you defined the vector indices to be incr=
easing with increasing powers of 10).  You've now done a multiplication ope=
ration, with the elements of the resulting vector corresponding to the digi=
ts of the result.</p><p>So, no reversal of vectors.  Just some number theor=
y post processing, which is nothing more than pulling out the "1s" place, a=
nd performing addition with the what's left.  I'm not saying you're wrong, =
just that if we're looking for atomic operations to simply express one thin=
g in terms of another, expressing multiplication in terms of correlation is=
 easy, and makes correlation look like the fundamental operation.<br>&lt;ed=
it&gt; Clarification of my goals.<br>&lt;edit&gt; Clarification of nomencla=
ture of correlation.</p></div></div><span class=3D"post-media"><ul data-rol=
